Well, I figure I'd update this thing now just to let ya'll know I'm still alive. Now that summer's here I've been busier than ever which is kind of odd but in a refreshing way. I've undertaken a self-designed research project about speech and gender, I work 40 hours a week at my dead-end job as a gas station attendant (it's a means to an end)and I work for a professor of morphology at Pitt. All in all I like what's going on so far but at times it's quite tiring. By the way, I also started taking Tai Ji Chung which is GREAT! I definitely recommend it to anyone, well, almost anyone. Ok, so I took the quiz that Daniel left a link to and of course I got "the black guy."

This survey looked interesting so I thought I'd take it. Well, the semester's almost over and I am quite grateful. I hope everyone did well on their finals. So, I've decided to do a research project of sorts about speech and gender and in particular differences between women and men's speech. Also, I will again attempt to tackle learning Navajo verbs but hopefully I'll have more success than I did last year. Ah! I almost forgot, I've been compiling a book of "strange" sayings that I've heard while residing in the hell-mouth commonly referred to as PITTsburgh. I'll start posting some of these expressions and words her for your amusement and bewilderment.

Heh, I thought the title was a bit interesting. Here's a thought, if you put the primary stress on either of the "saws" how does it affect the reading of this sentence to you. Note: Ignore the capital /s/ that kinda gives the intended reading away. Unfortunately I saw Saw this past Sunday and it sucked. Y? because the acting was basically non-existent throughout the entire move. I mean, I was pointing at the screen and laughing like a jackoff at some of the scenes because they were that bad. *sigh* I would have had more fun watching the Spongebob Squarepants movie. Anyways yesterday in morphology the five of us that showed up went over last week's homework and I got Pascual to amend one of his answers on the homework; it was fun to see him think. The question,as if you are interested, was asking why the word *abolishal doesn't exist in English (i.e. is commonly used) and his answer originally was because the suffix /-al/ can only attach to stems that have final stress (e.g. arrival and acquittal) but what he forgot to mention was that /-al/ is also a Latinate suffix that only attaches itself to Latinate bases. That's not a big deal but it's kinda important if you're dealing with several affixes that only attach themselves to stems that have final stress. Sorry, there's my rant for the day.
Is it bad if you wanna do your roomate? I mean sometimes you just wanna...you know, and it's like damn I'm so frustrated!

Well, I got bitched at for not writing more about Leslie, not really bitched at, just had a stern suggestion. Leslie Byrd (yeah it's a weird spelling) is a good friend of mine from high school. We weren't good friends then but we're closer now. She's blonde, fun loving and a year younger than me and she's the kind of girl who I thought would NEVER get married, not because she couldn't but because it just doesn't seem to be her "style." Her best friend during that time was Candace Dodge, the stereotypical "good girl" who, from what I hear is basically the same way now, but in college. Lelsie can sing very well as she was in the highest ranking chorus in our high school and sang at church too. She had this one annoying screeching thing she would do that was quite distrubing due to the shrillness it would produce in her voice. She's pretty outgoing and fun to be around so there's a summary introduction of The Byrd.

Sunday afternoon I had one of the best breakfasts that I've had since going home to Georgia. You see my awesome roomate who shall remain nameless for now cooked up this amazing breakfast of bacon (even though she doesn't eat pork), hot chocolate, wheat toast, and scrambled eggs. It tasted so good that I just had to keep on eating, even though I was full. That really made the day awesome.
Lelsie Byrd, a best high school friend is engaged to be married in July.

Last night at work I got hit on and wasn't even aware of it. Go me. I was making donuts and this girl comes in to buy something. She looked more Korean than Chinese but I wasn't sure because I was so engrossed in donut making. Anyways, while buying her stuff she says to my coworker,"The donuts smell good; I like chocolate eclairs." The thing is I wasn't even making any of those yet. I felt flattered. Heh, I also got high two days ago and learned a new term, "beat." I love languages.

So today I was finally doing some reading for my class on sociolinguistics and on one of the intro pages it has a quote by George Eliot which states, "'Correct English is the slang of pricks who write history and essays.'" I couldn't agree more. This is also going up as an away message. Yesterday was Jen's birthday, she's 21 so now she can legally drink. Her dad came to visit which was really cool because he's Sean Connery and therefore has to be cool. It's a scientific law. Today is Katie's birthday as well as Jen's mom's so the past two days have been pretty eventful in a the whole birthday sense.

I got a call from my aunt and she's gonna send me something; it should get here by the end of this week so that's exciting. They never call or send anything so I'm naturally expectant. My siblings haven't changed much but Zephaniah will be thirteen this year and, according to my aunt, might not be alive when/if I go down there for Christmas. We shall see. 'Tis all for now.

This is my most favorite class thus far. To be honest it's not east, there are so many terms to learn and so much esoteric data to analyze but it's been worth it so far. For example, we learned that the dictionary citation form in Arabic is the third person singular perfect. I have no intent of studying Arabic but I know this now. We also learn about words like the verb to hawk and the hideous infotainment, as well as the etymology of the disgusting word yinz (yunz), and how productive circumfixation is in the Romance languages. I am a huge nerd kill me now.
Sorry guys, I've gotta work on this color scheme a bit but for now I don't care that much but I'm sorry it's so ugly.

The Dao De Jing is a great book;it really helps one to get a different view on life and man's role in the universe. You all should read it.

I always feel that no matter what I do I don't/ can't achieve my goals, even the ones that are non-idealistic so to speak. This phrase means to get close to your goal but to not quite make it, to just barely miss the mark. Well, maybe my viewpoint will change one day....

Tonight after playing settlers at the apartment we had a discussion in which we basically discusses Andy Campbell's lack of religious beliefs. We finally concluded that he was an egotistical-non theist. This whole discussion began when he asked us if we could imagine ourselves and our lives without any religious influence whatsoever. He asked several times throughout the course of the discussion because we kept going on tangents trying to classify him by his belief "system." Every time he asked I thought, based on how I feel and know now, to take away any religious influence would be like taking a part of me and my culture away for it permeates many things and aspects of life. For some strange reason, thoughts about my past kept coming up and they upset me. I guess the chains of the past forged in the steel of pain and dissappointment aren't easily broken.

Oh my gosh! Last night I had the best night of my life and no it didn't involve alcohol.Jen the Druid,Ambrose the Braniac, and I were all hanging out in Brose's room and he was feeling down because he did badly on his Calc exam, so Jen started playing 80's music to try to cheer him up. It started to work but then all of a sudden Jen starts dancing, I mean, like club dancing and I was like,"Oh snap!" She was dancing to Def Leppard, Bon Jovi,and that kind of music but it was hot I mean I actually  wanted to kill her boyfrined for a few minutes. She was pretty hot and I had to make some self control rules. I made all of them too. They were kind of hard to make when she'd do stuff like teasingly lick chocolate pudding off of her fingers and do the tongue thing at me, I was like,"Scott(her boyfriend) is so stupid. Why hasn't he hit that yet?!"
    Yeah, her sitting on my lap made me want to grab my morals and throw them out of the window but I survived. I've never laughed so  much in my life! We made so many crude comments it wasn't even funny but it was. I'm getting hungry so I'll talk to ya'll later.

This is the last week of school and I'm glad, but I'm also saddened because I'll be leaving my friends.Despite their psychotic tendencies they're fun to be around. I wonder what I'll do at home besides go to work and church,all the time. Hopefully I'll get to hang out with my other good friends.We'll probably go swimming, have a cook out, and role play. I hope Sean gets better, his dad died a couple of weeks ago and he's one of my best friends. His dad was young too. I hope we can hang out.

Well,this Spring Break was very boring, except for the DND campaigns that we played during the week. Sean, you'll appreciate this, I got to use  my level six cleric;however, I couldn't use any of my great holy stuff and my armor class was dropped by fifteen points(that's understandable).

Sorry for not updating sooner folks, I kind of forgot about this place. Today has gone pretty well except for the writing test that I took in my Chinese writing class today. My KOrean friend went to a conference in D.C and I'm kind of bored right now.

Well, I got a hair cut yesterday which makes me look decent. I've been spending a lot of time with Yonnie which is cool and I hope that we can be more than just friends but if not, it's fun hanging out with her anyway. Yonnie is a girl from Hong Kong that I met at a CASA (Chinese American Students' Alliance) meeting a while ago(two months or so I believe). After that meeting she showed up in my Chinese writing class and we've been friends ever since. We're supposed tohang out today so I'm at the library trying to get osme work done before that time comes. I can't think of anything else to say so I'll say peace.
            Coniah b.k.a. Xiao Cai(4)

Well, guys, nothing extrememly exciting has happened yet. Today I studied for my Chinese class, we have an oral exam tomorrow, today. This weekend consisted of going to two study groups with some of my Chinese classmates, no, they're not all chinese they're just in my class. I'm doing laundry now and just checked my e-mail while waiting for the colored clothes to dry;I'll go to bed soon so I can finish my Spanish and Chinese homework. Bored, yeah. I watched Office Space with some newly made friends of mine yesterday evening. That's a funny movie.

Wow,
   It's only the second week of college and I'm already worn out. This weariness I contribute mainly to my Chinese class. It's very intense. We learn about 40 characters a week because by the end of this term we have to know approximately 400 characters and for our final we're going to have to write a four page paper completely in Chinese. I spend the bulk of my time studying Chinese writing, which is a lot to remember. Speaking is even more of a trip because they're some sounds that the Chinese have that we, being native English speakers don't have. The opposite is true also. In other words, I have to learn new sounds as well as unlearn old ones. This week in the practice class we went to our no English rule but today it was broken...by the teacher. One of my fellow classmates wasn't grasping the pronunciation of the word for yesterday which is, without the tones, zuotian. He just couldn't understand what he was trying to say. You see there three levels of speaking and writing classes and he's in the first year spoken class but he's not in the writing class like the majority of us are, so he's at a slight disadvantage. There are several asians in our class. There're two native Chineses, one Korean, and one Vietnamese. The Chinese speak Cantonese but we're learning Mandarin or Pinyin as it is sometimes called in the speaking class. The writing for them I guess is not difficult because the same characters are used in Pinyin and Cantonese; that kind of ticks me off. They're all cool though. Oh yeah, we have our Chinese classes back to back for a total of two hours everyday, making it a ten credit course, technically. It's all year as well, two terms long every year until the third expires. there's no fourth year class. Budo is interesting; we learn all kinds of things like roll falls, pressure points, and other universal components of the other popular and not so popular martial arts. Kendo is cool, it makes your legs hurt but it's a good kind of hurt. Sean would be glad to hear that I'm taking kendo; he's trying to do the same while he's in college. I really enjoy the discipline and respect in budo. You show respect to everyone, no matter what belt rank; I choose to bow to evryone except for my fellow white belts. Yes, I bow to the yellow belts. It's good as a workout and to just have fun and meet other people.

Well everybody college is good so far; until tomorrow that is when classes start. I'm thinking on majoring in Chinese and Spanish or a double major, if you will. I can't get my mailbox to work yet but I must for I'm expecting a check from my old emotionally exhausting job. Other than that I bought my textbooks yesterday and they only added up to $153.15;that wasn't all of them though. I met two girls who interest me their names are Preeti and Sana. Hmmmm Should I go for it try to get to know them a little better perhaps. Time will tell. Eric Neely a good friend of mine from high school imed me yesterday that was pretty cool. I spent most of yesterday downloading songs from the internet; alot of them are from my "backlslidden days" (the days that I had fun) in Michigan last summer as part of a pre-college program at an engineering school. As the old song goes "Precious memories,how they linger..." Well, back to downloading and I might go toan activities fair; they have info about an anime club. Later.

I actually was able to add two friends to my friends list which is good; now I'm hungry, I've been in the library for some time now with my uncle and this slow computer makes me even more anxious to get a new computer.  I'll have to talk to Sean about it first to make sure the computer I'm plannin' on buyin' is a wise choice.  I get ton move in a day before my roommate; but I have a na algebra placement exam to take tomorrow as I've already stated.  I don't want to do math, I want to chill some more and actually have a vacation.  I'm so glad that I'm not working at my local grocery store in Va anymore; of course I miss the people but the stress and hours they worked you were inhuman.  However, I have to get a job or two or three while I'm in college so I can pay for evrything that I want to have and have signed up to get.  I may apply for a job at a grocery store around campus as well as at one (or two) of the eateries surrounding the campus area.  There're so many places to eat at I'm going to be a vey happy freshman.  By the way, I have a little brown fridge that I'll be takin with me tomorrow; my roommate's bringin' a small television and a vcr so we'll be straight.
I'm trying to add friends to my friends list but it's not working so now I'm getting kind of twerked off.  Oh well.
